study findings will be reproducible 97% of the time","There is a 3% chance that the results occurred by random chance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA p-value of 0.03 means there is a \u003Cstrong\u003E3% chance that the results occurred by random chance\u003C/strong\u003E when the null hypothesis is true. In other words, if there truly was no difference between treatments, we would expect to see results this extreme or more extreme only 3% of the time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon misinterpretations include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe probability that the null hypothesis is true is 3%\u003C/strong\u003E - P-values do not measure the probability of hypotheses being true or false\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe treatment effect size is small\u003C/strong\u003E - P-values provide no information about the magnitude or importance of an effect\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe difference between groups is clinically significant\u003C/strong\u003E - A statistically significant result may or may not be clinically meaningful\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe study findings will be reproducible 97% of the time\u003C/strong\u003E - P-values do not predict future study outcomes or replication probability\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a p-value below 0.05 traditionally indicates statistical significance, it should not be used in isolation. Researchers should consider effect sizes, confidence intervals, and clinical context when interpreting study results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A p-value represents the probability of obtaining the observed results or more extreme, if there truly was no effect","Statistical significance (p\u003C0.05) does not automatically indicate practical or clinical importance","P-values should be interpreted alongside effect sizes and confidence intervals 